#  Day 84 – Visualizing GRC Metrics for Impact | 100 Days of GRC
*By Ibrahim Abdullahi | 100-Day GRC Challenge: Securing OpenMRS on AWS*

---

## From Numbers to Narrative

Day 83 designed the full KPI and KRI framework for the OpenMRS GRC program — twelve metrics across five control domains, each with a defined formula, data source, threshold, and trend interpretation guide. The framework answers the question: what should we measure? Day 84 answers the next question: how should we present what we measure so that the right people take the right action?

Metrics that exist only in the ISSO's monitoring log have no governance value. Metrics that reach the AO in a format the AO cannot parse in under two minutes are nearly as ineffective. The translation from raw monitoring data to governance-relevant visual presentation is where security programs most commonly fail to realize the value of the measurement work they have done.

I want to be honest about the tension in metrics visualization: there is a real temptation to make dashboards look good — to use design choices that emphasize green indicators and minimize the visual weight of yellow and red ones, to choose time ranges that show improvement rather than the full trend, to present a headline compliance percentage that masks the severity distribution underneath. These choices turn dashboards from governance tools into performance theater. Effective metrics visualization has to prioritize honesty over aesthetics, even when honest presentation creates uncomfortable conversations.

---

## What I Worked On Today

Today I work through the visualization design for the three distinct audiences identified in Day 83 — the ISSO operational view, the Health IT Manager / System Owner view, and the AO / Executive Director view — with specific design decisions for each audience and explicit attention to what should be visible rather than what would look best.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The insight that clarified visualization design today is the concept of information hierarchy — the idea that every dashboard presents information at multiple levels of detail, and the viewer should be able to read at the level of detail appropriate to their role without needing to navigate through levels that are not relevant to their decisions.

An executive reading the AO quarterly report should be able to answer "is the security program in good shape?" within 30 seconds by reading the headline indicators. If they want more detail on a specific indicator that is Yellow or Red, they should be able to find that detail in the next level down. The executive should not need to read through CVSS scores and CloudTrail log summaries to get the answer to their question.

An ISSO reviewing the operational dashboard should be able to see every metric, every threshold status, every trend direction, and every open item that requires action — all in one place, with the ability to navigate to the underlying data for any item that requires investigation.

The information hierarchy design principle means that different audiences do not need different data — they need the same data presented at different levels of aggregation with appropriate context for their decision-making role.

