## The Honest Dashboard Principle — Visualizing Bad News

The most important visualization decision is what to do when the news is bad. The CP-2 AT RISK status, the 13-minute RTO margin, the absent phishing simulation effectiveness metric — all of these are uncomfortable findings that a dashboard designer might be tempted to minimize or bury.

The right approach is the opposite: findings that represent genuine governance concerns should be visually prominent rather than visually minimized. The AO quarterly report's large yellow AT RISK box for Condition 1 is not an aesthetic choice — it is a governance signal. The AO's role requires them to know that a condition is at risk. A design that makes AT RISK look similar to MET is a design that has prioritized appearance over function.

This is the visualization equivalent of the documentation honesty principle from Day 80: a dashboard that always looks green because Yellow and Red indicators are minimized is producing metric theater. A dashboard that accurately represents the security program's state — including its challenges — is a governance tool that earns the trust of the people who rely on it.

