## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The visualization principle — information presented at the wrong level of detail for the audience fails to produce decisions — is directly illustrated by the **2012 South Carolina Department of Revenue breach**, in which 3.6 million taxpayer Social Security numbers and 387,000 credit and debit card numbers were exposed.

Post-incident investigation found that security monitoring tools had generated alerts that were present in technical staff dashboards. The technical team was aware of some unusual activity. What did not occur was the translation of that technical signal into governance-level communication that would have enabled leadership to make decisions — additional resources, accelerated patching, engagement with law enforcement — before the breach was complete.

The breach persisted for approximately 8 months. During that period, technical indicators were present but the communication bridge between the technical monitoring layer and the governance decision-making layer was not functioning. The metrics existed; the visualization and escalation that would have made them actionable to decision-makers did not.

For the OpenMRS program, the AO quarterly report's one-page visual summary is exactly the communication bridge that was absent in the South Carolina breach. The ISSO sees everything in the operational dashboard. The AO sees the governance-relevant picture in the quarterly summary. The connection between them — the escalation process that converts a Red indicator into an AO notification within 24 hours — is what makes the bridge functional rather than nominal.

