## What I Am Still Thinking About

The RTO margin trend visualization — the line chart with the current data point at 13-minute margin, the Yellow threshold at 60-minute margin, and the Red threshold at 30-minute margin — is the most useful single visualization in the entire dashboard because it makes a future problem visible today.

But the visualization only has governance value if the Health IT Manager and AO who see the 🟡 Yellow RTO margin actually understand what it means. A 13-minute RTO margin is not an intuitive concept for a clinician or an executive director who is not immersed in the contingency planning terminology.

The one-line explanation on the AO quarterly report — "Backup restoration within RTO target but margin narrowing; optimization in progress" — is the translation layer. But I am thinking about whether it is enough. An AO who sees "13-minute margin" and "optimization in progress" may not feel the urgency that 13 minutes from a failed RTO test should convey.

A better explanation might be: "The quarterly restoration test succeeded with 13 minutes to spare — the closest we have come to missing our 4-hour recovery target. At the current data growth rate, we may miss the target within 2 quarters without the optimization work in progress. The IT Administrator is actively addressing this." That explanation gives the AO the context — this is trending toward a real problem that is being actively managed — without requiring them to interpret the margin calculation themselves.

The principle: don't just display the metric. Interpret it. One sentence of honest interpretation per Yellow or Red indicator, written in non-technical language, makes the difference between a metric that informs and one that confuses.

